\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Work Order Linkage:
 The Vendor Compliance Record shall reference the work orders associated with vendor-related events including SLA breaches recorded under Policy 3.02 Section 6.5,
 enforcement actions received under Policy 5.01 Section 6.4,
 and maintenance events recorded under Policy 3.17 (System Maintenance and Vendor Repairs).
 The work order system is the operational evidence base;
 the Vendor Compliance Record is the compliance summary layer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Enforcement Notification Intake:
 When the IT Director provides written notification to the vendor compliance process under Policy 5.01 Section 6.4 (Contractors and Vendors),
 the Assistant IT Director shall log the notification in the applicable Vendor Compliance Record within two (2) business days of receipt.
 The log entry shall document the date the notification was received to establish the logging deadline.
 The log entry shall include the date of the enforcement action,
 the non-compliance identified,
 the IT-administrative action taken,
 the policy basis,
 the affected County systems or services,
 and the responsible contract administrator.
 Enforcement notifications shall be considered in the next scheduled vendor compliance review.
 Where two (2) or more enforcement notifications are received for the same vendor within any rolling twelve (12) month period,
 or where a single notification involves a Critical-severity incident or CJI exposure,
 the Assistant IT Director shall recommend to the IT Director that an unscheduled vendor compliance review be initiated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.2 Annual Vendor Compliance Review
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The Assistant IT Director shall conduct or coordinate a vendor compliance review for each vendor within scope no less than annually.
 The annual vendor compliance review establishes the minimum review floor;
 pre-renewal reviews under Section 6.3 and unscheduled reviews triggered under Section 6.1 or Section 6.5 are additional and do not reset the annual cycle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Review Inputs:
 Each vendor compliance review shall evaluate,
 at minimum:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Vendor SLA performance data for the review period,
 sourced from the Vendor Compliance Record and the vendor SLA performance tracking maintained under Policy 3.02 Section 6.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Enforcement notifications received during the review period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The currency and sufficiency of third-party assurance evidence under Section 6.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
CJIS Security Addendum compliance status,
 where applicable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The status of any open Corrective Action Plan associated with the vendor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Any vendor-related incidents,
 findings,
 or risk conditions identified during the review period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Review Output:
 The Assistant IT Director shall document each vendor compliance review in the Vendor Compliance Record.
 The review record shall include the date,
 the period covered,
 the data sources evaluated,
 a compliance determination for each evaluation criterion,
 an overall vendor compliance posture assessment,
 and any recommended actions.
 The compliance posture assessment shall use one of the following determinations:
 Compliant,
 Compliant with Observations,
 Non-Compliant —
 Remediation Required,
 or Non-Compliant —
 Contract Action Recommended.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Routing:
 A determination of Non-Compliant —
 Remediation Required shall initiate the vendor remediation and Corrective Action Plan routing defined in Section 6.6.
 A determination of Non-Compliant —
 Contract Action Recommended shall initiate the escalation process defined in Section 6.7.
 Observations identified under a Compliant with Observations determination shall be documented in the Vendor Compliance Record,
 communicated to the vendor in writing,
 and evaluated during the next scheduled vendor compliance review.
 Compliance review outcomes that constitute risk-relevant findings shall be referred to the IT Director for consideration as inputs to the Risk Register under Policy 1.09.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Unscheduled Reviews:
 The IT Director may authorize an unscheduled vendor compliance review at any time based on enforcement notification patterns,
 assurance evidence deficiencies,
 security incidents involving vendor systems or personnel,
 or other risk conditions.
 Unscheduled reviews shall follow the same input,
 output,
 and routing requirements as annual reviews.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.3 Pre-Renewal Compliance Evaluation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
No later than ninety (90) calendar days prior to the expiration or renewal date of any contract with a vendor within scope of this policy,
 the Assistant IT Director shall prepare a pre-renewal compliance evaluation and submit it to the IT Director for review.
 This evaluation aligns with and incorporates the vendor SLA performance summary required by Policy 3.01 (Service Catalog and SLA Policy) Section 6.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Evaluation Content:
 The pre-renewal compliance evaluation shall include,
 at minimum:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The complete Vendor Compliance Record history for the current contract period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A summary of the vendor's SLA performance across the contract period,
 sourced from Policy 3.02 Section 6.5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A summary of enforcement notifications received during the contract period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The status and outcome of all third-party assurance evidence evaluations during the contract period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The status and outcome of any Corrective Action Plans associated with the vendor during the contract period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
CJIS compliance status,
 where applicable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A compliance posture recommendation for the IT Director's consideration in the renewal decision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
IT Director Action:
 The IT Director shall review the pre-renewal compliance evaluation and document a renewal recommendation.
 The renewal recommendation shall be one of the following:
 Renew Without Conditions,
 Renew With Conditions (specifying the conditions),
 Do Not Renew,
 or Escalate to Contract Administrator and Legal Counsel.
 The documented renewal recommendation shall be provided to the Requesting Department Head identified in Policy 1.13 Section 3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Contracts Without Defined Renewal Dates:
 For evergreen contracts or contracts with automatic renewal provisions,
 the Assistant IT Director shall conduct the pre-renewal compliance evaluation annually,
 aligned with the annual vendor compliance review,
 and shall note the evaluation as serving both the annual review and the pre-renewal function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.4 Third-Party Assurance Evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For vendors whose services involve access to County data classified as Confidential or Restricted under Policy 1.11,
 or whose services involve access to CJI,
 the Information Operations Department shall maintain an ongoing program of third-party assurance evidence collection and evaluation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Assurance Evidence Types:
 Acceptable assurance evidence shall be restricted to the following approved artifact types:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Service Organization Control (SOC) reports (SOC 1,
 SOC 2 Type I,
 SOC 2 Type II).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Independent security assessments or penetration test summaries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Completed security questionnaires using County-defined or industry-standard formats.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Certifications or attestation letters from recognized bodies (e.g.,
 ISO 27001).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
CJIS Security Addendum Certifications required by Policy 1.13 Section 6.3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Any deviation from or substitution for these approved artifact types shall require documented IT Director approval.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Collection Cadence:
 The Assistant IT Director shall request updated assurance evidence from each vendor subject to this section no less than annually,
 or upon the issuance of new SOC reports or the renewal of relevant certifications.
 For CJIS vendors,
 the CJIS Security Addendum Certification and supporting CJIS compliance documentation shall be verified no less than annually and following any change in vendor personnel with CJI access.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Evaluation:
 The Assistant IT Director shall review each piece of assurance evidence received and document the evaluation in the Vendor Compliance Record.
 The evaluation shall note whether the evidence is current,
 whether it covers the services provided to the County,
 whether it identifies control deficiencies relevant to County risk,
 and whether any exceptions,
 qualifications,
 or findings in the evidence require County follow-up.
 Where assurance evidence reveals control deficiencies affecting County data or systems,
 the Assistant IT Director shall notify the IT Director and recommend whether the deficiency warrants a Corrective Action Plan under Policy 5.03,
 a contract action recommendation under Section 6.7,
 or an unscheduled vendor compliance review.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Failure to Provide:
 Where a vendor fails to provide requested assurance evidence within thirty (30) calendar days of the request,
 the Assistant IT Director shall escalate to the IT Director.
 The IT Director shall determine whether the failure constitutes a compliance concern warranting further action,
 including initiation of a Corrective Action Plan under Policy 5.03 or exercise of contractual audit rights.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.5 CJIS Vendor Compliance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
For vendors with logical access to CJI,
 or unescorted access to physically secure locations where CJI is processed,
 the following CJIS-specific compliance obligations apply in addition to the general requirements of this policy.
 These obligations operationalize the contractual audit and oversight rights established in Policy 1.13 Section 6.3 and the control assessment requirements of CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section CA-2 (Control Assessments).
 This policy governs the County's ongoing monitoring of CJIS vendor compliance after activation;
 it does not create,
 modify,
 or weaken the underlying contractual requirements established in Policy 1.13 Section 6.3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Triennial Assessment:
 The IT Director shall ensure that each CJIS vendor undergoes a compliance assessment no less than once every three (3) years,
 consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section CA-2.
 The assessment shall evaluate the vendor's implementation and operating effectiveness of controls applicable to CJI protection.
 The IT Director shall determine whether the assessment is conducted by Information Operations personnel,
 by an independent assessor,
 or through a combination of both,
 considering the objectivity requirements of CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section CA-2(1) (Independent Assessors) and the assessment resources available.
 Where internal personnel are utilized,
 the IT Director shall ensure the selected assessors possess organizational independence from the vendor management activities being assessed,
 consistent with the objectivity safeguards established in Policy 5.02 Section 6.4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Unannounced Inspections:
 The IT Director retains the authority to conduct unannounced security inspections of CJIS vendor operations,
 as provided by the contractual terms established under Policy 1.13 Section 6.3.
 The IT Director shall exercise this authority when risk conditions,
 enforcement notification patterns,
 or assurance evidence deficiencies indicate that a planned assessment may not provide sufficient assurance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Security Addendum Verification:
 The Assistant IT Director shall verify,
 no less than annually,
 that all CJIS vendor personnel with access to CJI have executed current CJIS Security Addendum Certifications as required by Policy 1.13 Section 6.3.
 Any gap in Security Addendum coverage shall be treated as a compliance deficiency and logged in the Vendor Compliance Record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Notification Agreements:
 Consistent with CJIS Security Policy v6.0:
 Section SR-8 (Notification Agreements) and NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 SA-9 (External System Services),
 the IT Director shall verify that each CJIS vendor's contract includes the incident notification and cooperation provisions required by Policy 1.13 Section 6.3.
 Where a CJIS vendor fails to meet the notification timelines established in Policy 1.13,
 the failure shall be documented in the Vendor Compliance Record and treated as a compliance deficiency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Findings Routing:
 CJIS assessment findings that constitute control deficiencies shall be routed to Policy 5.03 for Corrective Action Plan development.
 CJIS assessment findings that affect the authorization posture of a system processing CJI shall be provided to the IT Director for consideration under Policy 5.05 (Security Control Assessment and Authorization).
 CJIS assessment results shall be documented in the Vendor Compliance Record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.6 Vendor Remediation and Corrective Action Routing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
When a vendor compliance review under Section 6.2 produces a determination of Non-Compliant —
 Remediation Required,
 or when the IT Director determines that a vendor's cumulative compliance posture warrants formal remediation,
 the identified deficiencies shall be routed to the Corrective Action Plan (CAP) lifecycle governed by Policy 5.03.
 This policy defines the vendor-specific triggers and referral content;
 Policy 5.03 governs CAP development,
 tracking,
 and closure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
CAP Referral Content:
 The Assistant IT Director shall prepare the CAP referral and submit it to the IT Director for approval.
 The referral shall include:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The vendor name and applicable contracts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The specific compliance deficiencies or performance failures that triggered the referral.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The affected County systems or services.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The contract administrator responsible for the vendor relationship.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Any interim risk mitigation measures in effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Vendor Notification:
 Upon IT Director approval of the CAP referral,
 the Assistant IT Director shall provide written notification to the vendor and to the Requesting Department Head.
 The notification shall identify the deficiencies,
 the required remediation outcomes,
 and the CAP timeline established under Policy 5.03.
 Vendor notification is an operational communication;
 it does not require vendor agreement or acceptance to take effect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Monitoring:
 The Assistant IT Director shall update the Vendor Compliance Record with the CAP reference and shall monitor vendor-related CAP progress as part of each subsequent scheduled vendor compliance review.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Closure or Escalation:
 Where the vendor achieves the required remediation outcomes within the CAP timeline,
 the Assistant IT Director shall document the resolution in the Vendor Compliance Record.
 Where a vendor-related CAP fails to achieve closure within the approved timeline,
 or where the vendor's compliance posture deteriorates during the CAP period,
 the Assistant IT Director shall recommend escalation to contract action under Section 6.7.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Clarification:
 Observations that do not meet the threshold for formal CAP development shall be documented in the Vendor Compliance Record and communicated to the vendor in writing.
 The observations shall be evaluated during the next scheduled vendor compliance review.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.7 Escalation and Contract Action Recommendations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
When a vendor compliance review under Section 6.2 produces a determination of Non-Compliant —
 Contract Action Recommended,
 or when a vendor-related Corrective Action Plan under Section 6.6 fails to achieve closure,
 the Assistant IT Director shall prepare a formal contract action recommendation for IT Director review.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Recommendation Content:
 The contract action recommendation shall include,
 at minimum:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
A summary of the vendor's compliance history from the Vendor Compliance Record.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The specific compliance deficiencies or CAP failures that support the recommendation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The recommended action (which may include contract modification,
 contract non-renewal,
 contract termination for cause,
 or other contractual remedy as applicable).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
The potential operational impact of the recommended action on County services.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
IT Director Action:
 The IT Director shall review the contract action recommendation and determine the appropriate course of action.
 Where the IT Director concurs with the recommendation,
 the IT Director shall refer the matter to the contract administrator and County legal counsel for contract remedies,
 consistent with the referral pathway established in Policy 5.01 Section 6.4 (Contractors and Vendors).
 The IT Director's authority to revoke or restrict system access under Policy 5.01 is independent of the contract remedy process and may be exercised at any point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Documentation:
 All contract action recommendations,
 IT Director determinations,
 and referrals shall be documented in the Vendor Compliance Record and retained in accordance with Section 6.9.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.8 Vendor Performance Data Feed
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
This policy serves as a source data provider for the Vendor Performance KPI domain established in Policy 5.04 Section 6.2.
 The Assistant IT Director shall ensure that vendor compliance review outcomes,
 CAP status,
 assurance evidence currency,
 and CJIS compliance status are available for incorporation into the Quarterly KPI Review Summary prepared under Policy 5.04 Section 6.5.
 This data feed supplements the vendor SLA performance data provided by Policy 3.02 Section 6.5 and shall not duplicate data already captured in the service level management function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*

\lang english
6.9 Record Retention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Records generated under this policy shall be retained in accordance with NRS 239.125 and the Nevada Local Government Records Retention Schedule.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Vendor Compliance Records:
 Vendor Compliance Records,
 including all compliance review records,
 assurance evidence evaluations,
 enforcement notification logs,
 CAP referrals,
 and contract action recommendations,
 shall be retained in the System of Engagement (Redmine) for six (6) calendar years after the record is closed,
 in accordance with LRDA 20071300 (Vendor Performance Case Files).
 A Vendor Compliance Record is closed when the vendor no longer provides services to the County and all open compliance actions,
 Corrective Action Plans,
 and contract action recommendations associated with the vendor have been resolved or formally closed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
CJIS Assessment Records:
 For vendors with access to CJI,
 assessment records shall be retained for the greater of the LRDA 20071300 retention period or the CJIS-required retention period applicable at the time of the assessment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Litigation and Legal Holds:
 The IT Director shall ensure that retention and disposition actions are suspended during litigation holds,
 public records preservation requirements,
 or other legal hold events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\lang english
Public Records:
 All records generated under this policy are subject to NRS 239 and may be subject to public disclosure unless protected by a specific statutory exemption.
 Disclosure determinations for vendor compliance records containing security findings,
 assurance evidence,
 or CJIS-related materials shall be made in coordination with the County's public records process and legal counsel,
 consistent with applicable exemptions and the data classification requirements of Policy 1.11.
\end_layout

